CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER, NEW OUTBREAK - NETHERLANDS
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Fri, 05 Sep 1997 14:11:20 -0300
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
[see
Classical Swine Fever - Netherlands (Gelderland) 970802215151
Classical Swine Fever - Netherlands (Gelderland)(02) 970805232635]
Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol. 10, No. 36
Follow-up report No. 7: Text of an e-mail received on 1 September 1997 from
Dr C.C.J.M. van der Meijs, Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture,
Nature Management and Fisheries, The Hague
End of previous report period: 11 August 1997. End of this report period: 1
September 1997.
Location of the new outbreak: Schoondijke city (51o 21' N - 3o 33' E),
Zeeuws-Vlaanderen region, Zeeland province.
Total number of outbreaks identified since 1 January 1997: three hundred and
ninety (390).
Description of affected population in the outbreak in Zeeland: fattening herd.
Total number of animals in the outbreak in Zeeland:
susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
42,424 42,424 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Institute for Animal Science and
Health of the Department of Agricultural Research (ID-DLO), Lelystad.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent/origin of infection: unknown. Infected pigs were
introduced about 15 July 1997. So far, there are indications that the
infection was introduced through a lorry that had not been thoroughly
cleansed and disinfected.
B. Other epidemiological details: this outbreak, which was detected on 26
August 1997, is the first in Zeeland province.
Control measures during reporting period: stamping out; protection zone and
surveillance zone; 20-km-radius buffer zone around the outbreak; total
standstill on all cattle, semen, lorries and manure.
--
Dorothy Preslar
ProMED/AHEAD Program Officer
e-mail: <dpreslar@fas.org>
